english:
  title: On the Hawk and the Chicken
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    During the reign of Yongneung, there was a clerk attached to the Hawk Office who once fed a chicken to a hawk. The hawk devoured nearly the entire wing of the chicken, leaving it to die. The dying bird was placed in a cloth bag, yet at dawn it still managed to cry out. When word of this reached the ruler, his heart was moved to pity. Thereafter, the court deliberated and abolished the practice.

    The ordinary cry of a chicken is but its nature—we hear it unmoved. Yet when an injured chicken cries once, the ruler's heart stirs and the nation disbands an entire office. This reveals what we must understand: compassion is inherent in the human heart from the beginning.

    At that time, people served the hawk. Those who climbed trees became lame. Those who worked the seas saw their boats capsize and drowning men lost. The setting of snares multiplied, the outfitting of falconers compounded. Livestock were seized, crops trampled. How could people's grievances about the hawk's harm amount to merely one chicken's cry?

    A chicken is no match for human eloquence, yet many voices go unheeded while a single bird's cry moves the ruler. From humans down through all creatures—furred deer, rabbits, foxes, and wildcats; feathered geese, cranes, ducks, and doves—all receive its blessing. This is because human speech is contrived, while a chicken's cry flows from pure, unforced sincerity.

    The human heart, you see, is clouded by mere words yet illumined by direct truth. King Xuan of Qi could not bear to watch a single ox led to slaughter—this was a compassionate heart. Yet he failed to heed Mencius' teaching on humane governance. The Book of Documents says: "Protect the people as you would cherish an infant." Had the ruler possessed from the start a parent's heart toward his people, why would he need a chicken's cry to move him to pity?

    The ruler favors hawks. Had Long Fang or Bi Gan remonstrated in court, he would surely have raged and executed them—all the ministers knew this well. Yet when the ruler's heart was moved to compassion, that was the moment to guide him gently toward wisdom. Instead, they spoke not of abolishing it then, but waited for the incident at Yuanyang before at last ending the practice. Alas, even that came too late.
  footnotes:
    - Yongneung (永陵) refers to the reign of King Sejo of Joseon
    - Dragon Fang (龍逄) and Bi Gan (比干) were legendary officials known for their principled remonstrations that led to their deaths
    - Yuanyang (岳陽) likely refers to a specific incident where the ruler's heart was further moved
    - The reference to King Xuan of Qi recalls Mencius' famous anecdote about the king's inability to watch an ox be slaughtered, used to illustrate innate human compassion
